<font color="#FF0000">PICTURES OR COMPASSION</font><br>
<tt>Sat May  3  2:44:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have been off the line (literally) for the last four days as the phone lines to the local provider were down.  So I apologize for not responding in order.<br><br>
Doc Del was very perceptive about the photographers and M.P.'s who did not help Kim Phuc, if a bit graphic about his response (and yes, I have fished and know the difference, Doc.  The reason that this is important is that these people did not see themselves as participants in the event.  The M.P.'s may have had their orders, but the photograghers had only their &quot;story&quot; in mind, and not the concerns of the people around them.  <br><br>
We, in society now, sometimes have this same response.  The American Red Cross, in its first aid training, is actively trying to overcome the complacency of people when facing an emergency situation.  <br><br>
I would encourage all of us to take this first aid training, then commit to helping in these situations.  And to hell with the photograph and the &quot;prizes&quot; that they would win from someone's suffering.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


